        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We aim to target both the CO(6-5) and CO(5-4) rotational emission lines at z=5.1245, and hence require observations at 94.1 GHz and 113GHz (i.e. ALMA band 3). Our existing detection of the CO(2-1) line in J104043.50-115756.8 has a velocity FWHM of 110 km/s and, in the absence of further information, we assume that the higher order line emission traces the same range of velocities.  At this frequency, a line with FWHM~100 km/s will span ~40 MHz. Hence we chose a 2GHz bandwidth (i.e. relatively low spectral resolution) at each frequency and expect to rebin and smooth over a number of channels.

As is the case with many high redshift galaxies, our information on the projected angular size of this source is limited. The CO line detection in J104043.50-115756.8 is an unresolved point source with a beam size of 7x5'' (45x30 kpc comoving at z~5), but this is many times larger than the projected size of any known (unlensed) z~5 galaxy suggesting that the true size is much smaller. Lyman break galaxies at this redshift have a characteristic size ~0.2'' in the optical. No optical detection exists for J104043.50-115756.8, and the possible near-infrared counterpart is also an unresolved point source, this time at sub-arcsecond resolution.

We thus make the assumption that J104043.50-115756.8 is an unresolved point source at the resolution of ALMA at this frequency (&lt;1.2'') as would be expected for Lyman break galaxies. Certainly it seems unlikely that emission exists on scales beyond the ~8'' largest scale as this should have been detectable even convolved with the beam of the ATCA. 

Our CO(2-1) emission line was detected with a peak flux of 0.94+/-0.15 mJy/beam. Without a strong prior constraint, we set our target depth based on an extrapolation of the expected CO excitation ladder. Given an excitation level between that of low intensity starbusts and an SMG (see figure 4), we expect I_(5-4)/I_(2-1) ~ 5. Hence, we expect a peak flux at 94.1 GHz of ~4.8mJy and we set a target rms at this frequency of 0.48 mJy/beam in a 100 km/s channel - anticipating a 10 sigma detection, but allowing flexibility to resolve the line at higher excitations, or secure a better than 5 sigma detection at lower excitations. According to the the ALMA OT sensitivity calculator, assuming an unresolved point source, 34 antennae and default weather conditions, this requires 10.45 minutes of on-source integration.  In the same integration time, we will reach an rms at 113 GHz of ~0.6 mJy - allowing us also to secure an expected 10 sigma detection on the CO (6-5) line.

At the same time, we propose to use the full bandwidth available (4x1875 MHz) to obtain a continuum flux for this source with an rms of 30 uJy (based on the required time for the line experiment). This will provide an SED point longwards of the peak of dust emission at this redshift, potentially allowing improved temperature constraints - particularly if a band 7 point is also obtained (see related proposal).
</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
