    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>While great progress has been made in investigating galaxies at high redshifts (z&gt;5) over recent years, investigations have been limited to a few classes of objects. Unless a galaxy is dust-free and ultraviolet-luminous (Lyman break galaxies) or massive and intensely starbursting (SMGs or QSO hosts), it cannot identified by conventional techniques. However investigations at millimeter wavelengths have identified what may be the first galaxies of moderate mass and star formation intensity detected initially through molecular line emission.

Galaxy J104043.50-115756.8 at z=5.1245 exhibits CO(2-1) line emission at a redshift consistent with that of two neighbouring Lyman break galaxies. Here we propose observations at 94/113 GHz, probing the CO J=5-4/6-5 emission lines at z=5 and the millimetre flux in this source. Using ALMA it is possible to far exceed the sensitivity obtained in our previous work in a mere 10 min of integration time. In addition to unambiguously confirming the redshift, in combination with our J=2-1 line detection we will use excitation models to constrain the excitation and gas properties in this source.
</prp:abstract>
